<h2>Iowa Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Iowa offers several incentive programs that make solar panels and efficient HVAC systems more affordable for residents and businesses. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar installations through 2032, then steps down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost including equipment, installation, and related expenses, making it one of the most valuable solar incentives available.</p>

<p>At the state level, Iowa provides a property tax exemption for solar energy systems, meaning the added value of a solar installation won't increase property tax obligations. This exemption applies to both residential and commercial installations and remains in effect for the life of the system. Additionally, Iowa offers net metering through MidAmerican Energy and other utilities, allowing solar system owners to receive credit for excess electricity produced by their systems.</p>

<p>MidAmerican Energy operates several programs supporting energy efficiency and renewable energy adoption. Their rebate programs for high-efficiency HVAC equipment can provide hundreds of dollars in incentives for qualifying installations. The utility also offers time-of-use rate schedules that can benefit solar system owners by providing higher compensation for electricity produced during peak demand periods. Some municipalities and counties in Iowa offer additional local incentives, property tax abatements, or expedited permitting for renewable energy projects.</p>

<p>For HVAC systems, federal tax credits are available for qualifying heat pump installations, including air-source and geothermal systems. The Inflation Reduction Act extended and expanded these credits, providing up to \$2,000 in tax credits for heat pump installations and additional credits for electrical panel upgrades needed to support high-efficiency electric systems. Iowa utilities frequently offer rebates for Energy Star certified equipment, with rebate amounts varying by system type and efficiency rating.</p>

